data: {"id":"a9e7799f-52b9-473b-b8b4-e53ed428bc4c","model":"gpt-35-turbo","created":1701985443,"object":"extensions.chat.completion.chunk","choices":[{"index":0,"delta":{"context":{"messages":[{"role":"tool","content":"{\"citations\":[{\"content\":\"<h2 id=\\\"ai-cognitive-services-sdk-releases\\\">AI Cognitive Services SDK Releases</h2>\\n<ul>\\n<li>\\\"When's the next release?\\\"</li>\\n<li>\\\"How long is there left to get this change in?\\\"</li>\\n<li>\\\"When did we release that old version?\\\"</li>\\n</ul>\\n<h3 id=\\\"current-in-development-release\\\">Current, in-development release</h3>\\n<table>\\n<thead>\\n<tr>\\n<th>Sprint Label</th>\\n<th>Version - Speech</th>\\n<th>Version - Vision</th>\\n<th>All PRs out</th>\\n<th>Release by</th>\\n<th>Notes</th>\\n</tr>\\n</thead>\\n<tbody>\\n<tr>\\n<td>202301</td>\\n<td>1.25.0</td>\\n<td>0.7</td>\\n<td>Fri Jan 13</td>\\n<td>Fri Jan 27</td>\\n<td></td>\\n</tr>\\n</tbody>\\n</table>\\n<p><strong>\\\"PR complete\\\" and \\\"release by\\\"</strong></p>\\n<p>We generally talk about two dates when it comes to upcoming releases:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><strong>PR complete</strong> or <strong>\\\"all PRs out by\\\"</strong>: this is the date when all pull requests that are intended to be part of the release should be functionally complete and out for review. It's OK if it still needs a few updates, but expectations on pending PRs should be that they'll wrap up within a business day or two. This is what's tracked in our sprints.</li>\\n<li><strong>Release</strong> or <strong>\\\"release by\\\"</strong>: This is roughly the \\\"P95\\\" estimate for the latest the publicly-available release packages are published and available under the assumption that the corresponding PR complete date holds. This is an <em>estimate</em> that's intended to be conservative -- most releases happen before the projected date, but <strong>release is always gated by readiness</strong> and it's possible for things to get postponed. Estimated release dates may be communicated to customers, but only with the clarification that it's a target and not a guarantee.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>The single \\\"source of truth\\\" for the SDK's \\\"PR complete\\\" date is the sprint definition on Azure DevOps: <a href=\\\"https://msasg.visualstudio.com/Skyman/_sprints/taskboard/Carbon%20Team/Skyman/Carbon/\\\">https://msasg.visualstudio.com/Skyman/_sprints/taskboard/Carbon%20Team/Skyman/Carbon/</a></p>\\n<p>See the sprint date range definition in the upper right, e.g.:</p>\\n<p><img alt=\\\"image\\\" src=\\\"https://media.microsoft.ghe.com/user/5475/files/00c74e6f-de09-45dc-ae56-2954ee12006d\\\" /></p>\\n<p>\\\"Release by\\\" dates, meanwhile, are generally estimated at about two weeks past PR complete -- time enough for in-flight PRs to wrap up, release candidates to be built and validated across all languages/environments, documentation and other external repository resources to be staged, and bits to be published.</p>\\n<p>The dates here are replicated for convenience and history. This may not always be entirely up to date; please check the sprint board above or contact the team (cdev) if anything's unclear!</p>\\n<h3 id=\\\"release-planning\\\">Release planning</h3>\\n<p><a href=\\\"./planning.md\\\">SDK planning -- Wiki</a></p>\\n<h3 id=\\\"release-signoff\\\">Release signoff</h3>\\n<p><a href=\\\"https://microsoft.sharepoint.com/teams/Carbon2/_layouts/OneNote.aspx?id=%2Fteams%2FCarbon2%2FSiteAssets%2FCarbon%20Notebook&amp;wd=target%28Release.one%7C47758B05-9653-4BA3-B15F-0737A0AB5880%2F%29\\\">SDK release process -- OneNote</a></p>\",\"id\":null,\"title\":\"AI Cognitive Services SDK Releases\",\"filepath\":\"release.md\",\"url\":\"https://openaisdktestdatastorage.blob.core.windows.net/fileupload-azure_search_index/release.md\",\"metadata\":{\"chunking\":\"orignal document size=1000. Scores=6.6608486Org Highlight count=30.\"},\"chunk_id\":\"0\"},{\"content\":\"<p>Notes</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>\\n<p>If you get a build errors similar to <code>D:\\\\src\\\\carbon\\\\build\\\\source\\\\bindings\\\\csharp\\\\Microsoft.CognitiveServices.Speech.csharp.csproj : error NU1301: Unable to load the service index for source https://pkgs.dev.azure.com/msasg/skyman/_packaging/skyman_PublicPackages/nuget/v3/index.json</code>, open a Poswer Shell terminal and run the following: <code>iex \\\"&amp; { $(irm https://aka.ms/install-artifacts-credprovider.ps1) } -AddNetfx\\\"</code></p>\\n</li>\\n<li>\\n<p>In case you change the carbon.h interface, make sure to update the CMakefile.txt for the swig layer to reflect any change in the generated files (generated files are added/removed). This is currently due to a cmake limitation that does not allow for wildcard specifications (at least for the jar generation part).</p>\\n</li>\\n<li>\\n<p>If you want to include the csharp project into the solution, edit source/bindings/csharp/CMakeLists.txt and change set(USECSPROJ TRUE) to be set(USECSPROJ FALSE), then run cmake again. Please don't check in the change.</p>\\n</li>\\n<li>\\n<p>If you see \\\"error 9009\\\" failures in the NuGet restore projects, it typically indicates that devenv.exe can't access NuGet.exe (you can check the full output to verify). Try moving it to an unprotected location in your system-wide PATH (e.g. <code>C:\\\\tools</code> instead of <code>C:\\\\windows\\\\system32</code>)</p>\\n</li>\\n<li>\\n<p>If you see \\\"error MSB4236: The SDK 'Microsoft.NET.Sdk' specified could not be found.\\\" as a build failure reason, see <a href=\\\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/64679752/13474899\\\">this SO answer</a></p>\\n</li>\\n<li>\\n<p>If you see \\\"LNK2001 unresolved external symbol HTTPAPI_GetLastError Microsoft.CognitiveServices.Speech.core\\\" trying to build in Visual Studio, run \\\"git submodule update\\\" from the CLI to sync to the latest Azure-C-Shared submodule</p>\\n</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>Back to <a href=\\\"index.md\\\">Carbon main page</a> page.</p>\",\"id\":null,\"title\":\"Checkout and Build Carbon on Windows\",\"filepath\":\"setupwinenv.md\",\"url\":\"https://openaisdktestdatastorage.blob.core.windows.net/fileupload-azure_search_index/setupwinenv.md\",\"metadata\":{\"chunking\":\"orignal document size=610. Scores=0.27400258Org Highlight count=1.\"},\"chunk_id\":\"0\"},{\"content\":\"<p>Create Carbon CMake files and VS solutions</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Create a <code>build</code> directory <strong>inside</strong> the local <code>Carbon</code> repository directory by typing:</li>\\n</ul>\\n<pre><code class=\\\"language-cmd\\\"> cd Carbon\\n mkdir build\\n cd build\\n</code></pre>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Open an admin command prompt, and cd to the Carbon folder</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>At this point, <strong>From your build folder</strong>, running <code>cmake ..</code> <strong>as administrator</strong> (nb: the <code>..</code> for \\\"parent directory\\\" is vital and easy to miss) will generate default-configuration cmake and VS solutions for both Release and Debug builds. It will not yet compile source code. However, it may be that these defaults <strong>do not meet your needs</strong>, so continue reading before running cmake.</p>\\n<p>Alternately, if you want to maintain lowest privledges for each task instead of running the build as an administrator you can grant yourself symbolic link permissions in three steps:\\n1) Create a local group to have the permission:\\n C:\\\\Windows\\\\system32&gt; net localgroup /add SymLinkUsers\\n2) Add youself to the group:\\n net localgroup /add SymLinkUsers <alias>@microsoft.com\\n3) In the Local SecurityPolcy under Local Policies-&gt;User Rights Assignment add the \\\"SymLinkUsers\\\" group.\\n (You will need to be sure to select \\\"groups\\\" from the Ojbect Types)\\n(The path is convoluted because AAD joined machines cannot directly assign rights to AAD accounts).</p>\\n<pre><code>#### Default build configuration\\n</code></pre>\\n<ul>\\n<li>By default, the VS2022 generator will be used, equivalent to <code>-G \\\"Visual Studio 17 2022\\\"</code> (<a href=\\\"https://cmake.org/cmake/help/latest/manual/cmake-generators.7.html\\\">read more about generators here</a>)</li>\\n<li>By default, C++, C#, Java and Python APIs will be built. This is equivalent to specifying <code>-DBUILD_JAVA=\\\"ON\\\" -DBUILD_CSHARP=\\\"ON\\\" -DBUILD_PYTHON=\\\"ON\\\"</code>. You can specify <code>=\\\"OFF\\\"</code> for any one of them to turn off that language. For example, run <code>cmake .. -DBUILD_JAVA=\\\"OFF\\\" -DBUILD_CSHARP=\\\"OFF\\\" -DBUILD_PYTHON=\\\"OFF\\\"</code> to only build C++.</li>\\n<li>No extensions are built by default. See below for a table of supported extensions (e.g. keyword spotting)</li>\\n</ul>\",\"id\":null,\"title\":\"Checkout and Build Carbon on Windows\",\"filepath\":\"setupwinenv.md\",\"url\":\"https://openaisdktestdatastorage.blob.core.windows.net/fileupload-azure_search_index/setupwinenv.md\",\"metadata\":{\"chunking\":\"orignal document size=665. Scores=0.25928485Org Highlight count=1.\"},\"chunk_id\":\"1\"},{\"content\":\"<p>Customize your build for Embedded Speech</p>\\n<p>Embedded speech (recognition, synthesis) support is not enabled by default. To enable it, download and configure the following external components:\\n* ONNX runtime\\n * Download build artifacts as instructed in <code>external\\\\onnx_runtime\\\\README.md</code>.</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>SR runtime and models</li>\\n<li>Download build artifacts as instructed in <code>external\\\\sr_runtime\\\\README.md</code>.</li>\\n<li>Add <code>-DEXTENSION_RNNT_ENABLED=true</code> to Carbon <code>cmake</code> options to enable the feature.</li>\\n<li>It is not necessary to download all SR models if not specifically needed. <code>cxx_api_tests</code> uses <code>FP\\\\en-US\\\\V4\\\\onnx</code> and whatever the latest <code>FP\\\\en-US\\\\V#\\\\onnx</code> and <code>FP\\\\de-DE\\\\V#\\\\onnx</code> models are (<code>#</code> = the highest version number available).</li>\\n<li>If running <code>cxx_api_tests</code>, add <code>--offlineModelPathList=path\\\\to\\\\model(s)</code> to command-line options.</li>\\n<li>\\n<p>Complete embedded SR tests require also embedded TTS, as well as KWS and GStreamer (see <em>Customized extensions</em> in this document).</p>\\n</li>\\n<li>\\n<p>TTS runtime and voices</p>\\n</li>\\n<li>Download build artifacts as instructed in <code>external\\\\offline_tts\\\\README.md</code>.</li>\\n<li>\\n<p>Add <code>-DEXTENSION_HYBRID_TTS_ENABLED=true</code> to Carbon <code>cmake</code> options to enable the feature.</p>\\n</li>\\n<li>\\n<p>1DS C/C++ SDK libraries for embedded speech telemetry on Windows</p>\\n</li>\\n<li>Download build artifacts as instructed in <code>external\\\\cpp_client_telemetry_windows\\\\README.md</code>.</li>\\n</ul>\\n<h4 id=\\\"customized-extensions\\\">Customized extensions</h4>\\n<p>Carbon builds a variety of optional <em>extensions</em> that aren't included in the build project by default. Each has a set of setup instructions, usually involving downloading a build artifact, and each has a cmake flag to enable it in your local build.\\n The \\\"source of truth\\\" for these extensions is the CMakeLists.txt file in the root folder of your clone; search for \\\"EXTENSION_\\\" or \\\"DEXTENSION\\\". As a snap:</p>\\n<table>\\n<thead>\\n<tr>\\n<th>Extension</th>\\n<th>Vision/Speech</th>\\n<th>Build parameter</th>\\n<th>Uses folders</th>\\n</tr>\\n</thead>\\n<tbody>\\n<tr>\\n<td>KWS</td>\\n<td>Speech</td>\\n<td><code>-DEXTENSION_KWS_ENABLED=\\\"ON\\\"</code></td>\\n<td><code>Carbon\\\\external\\\\KWS</code> (See README.md there)</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Audio Compression<br>(Sending Silk audio to the cloud)</td>\\n<td>Speech</td>\\n<td><code>-DEXTENSION_AUDIOCOMPRESSION_ENABLED=\\\"ON\\\"</code></td>\\n<td><code>Carbon\\\\source\\\\extensions\\\\audio-compression</code><br> (TODO is this still used? <code>Carbon\\\\external\\\\silk-codec</code>)</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>GStreamer decoder support<br>(Decoding compressed input audio)</td>\\n<td>Speech</td>\\n<td><code>-DEXTENSION_CODEC_ENABLED=\\\"ON\\\"</code></td>\\n<td><code>Carbon\\\\source\\\\extensions\\\\codec</code><br><code>Carbon\\\\external\\\\gstreamer-android</code><br><code>Carbon\\\\external\\\\gstreamer-windows</code></td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Media source</td>\\n<td>Vision</td>\\n<td><code>-DEXTENSION_MEDIA_SOURCE_INGESTION_ENABLED=\\\"ON\\\"</code></td>\\n<td><code>carbon\\\\external\\\\media-source-ingestion</code></td>\\n</tr>\\n</tbody>\\n</table>\\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> See the instructions in each extension's folder, e.g. <code>carbon/external/kws/readme.md</code>, to ensure a successful local build.</p>\",\"id\":null,\"title\":\"Checkout and Build Carbon on Windows\",\"filepath\":\"setupwinenv.md\",\"url\":\"https://openaisdktestdatastorage.blob.core.windows.net/fileupload-azure_search_index/setupwinenv.md\",\"metadata\":{\"chunking\":\"orignal document size=1194. Scores=0.25740328Org Highlight count=1.\"},\"chunk_id\":\"2\"},{\"content\":\"<h1 id=\\\"checkout-and-build-carbon-on-windows\\\">Checkout and Build Carbon on Windows</h1>\\n<h3 id=\\\"setup\\\">Setup</h3>\\n<table>\\n<thead>\\n<tr>\\n<th>Resource</th>\\n<th></th>\\n<th>Notes</th>\\n</tr>\\n</thead>\\n<tbody>\\n<tr>\\n<td>CMake</td>\\n<td>Required</td>\\n<td>https://cmake.org/download/ -- The cmake version should be &gt;= 3.16. (You're best bet is to use teh same version that the ADO lab agents are using as you know that'll work see https://github.com/actions/runner-images/blob/main/images/win/Windows2022-Readme.md to find that version) Under \\\"Binary distributions\\\", click on the .msi file next to \\\"Windows win64-x64 Installer\\\". During installation, select \\\"Add CMake to the system PATH for all users\\\" or for \\\"current user\\\".</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>NuGet</td>\\n<td>Required</td>\\n<td>https://www.nuget.org/downloads -- Not an installer, so put <code>nuget.exe</code> somewhere on your system path (e.g. <code>Windows\\\\System32</code> from an admin command prompt)</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Visual Studio 2022</td>\\n<td><em>Recommended</em></td>\\n<td>https://visualstudio.microsoft.com -- You can use vscode or other environments as an IDE, but Visual Studio is the standard and a great place to start. Grab the Enterprise edition from . Include <code>.NET desktop development</code>, <code>Desktop development with C++</code>, and <code>Python development</code> as workloads, or run the Visual Studio Installer if you need to add these workloads to an existing install.</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td></td>\\n<td></td>\\n<td>Recommended extension: <strong>StopOnFirstBuildError</strong>. The Carbon Visual Studio project has lots of solution in it. When you develop code using VS, sometimes you want the build to stop on the first build error. Otherwise, it will continue on to try and build all the solutions in the project. To install the extension, open Visual Studio 2022 (you can select \\\"continue without code...\\\"), Select Extension --&gt; Manage Extensions --&gt; Online, and search for StopOnFirstBuildError. Select and install it. This is a <a href=\\\"https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=EinarEgilsson.StopOnFirstBuildError\\\">direct link</a> to the VS marketplace page for this extension. Once the extension is installed, you will see a \\\"Stop build on first error\\\" check box in the VS build menu (only visible in a multi-project solution)</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Python</td>\\n<td>Required<br/>(For Python)</td>\\n<td>https://www.python.org/downloads/windows/ -- Install Python 3.x.x (be sure to pick the 64-bit version!)</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td>Java</td>\\n<td>Required<br/>(for Java)</td>\\n<td>https://www.azul.com/downloads/zulu -- In the section \\\"Download Zulu Builds of OpenJDK\\\" go to the latest build, find the Windows 64-bit row, and click on the .msi link. Install it in the default folder.</td>\\n</tr>\\n<tr>\\n<td></td>\\n<td></td>\\n<td>Add <code>JAVA_HOME</code> as a global environment variable. For example, if you install <code>Zulu 15</code> using the default path, set the environment variable <code>JAVA_HOME</code> to <code>C:\\\\Program Files\\\\zulu\\\\zulu-15</code>, if this wasn't done by the installer already. To set an environment variable, click on the Windows Start icon, start typing \\\"environment\\\" --&gt; click on \\\"edit environment variables for your account\\\" --&gt; \\\"Environment Variables\\\". Add/update the system variables as needed.</td>\\n</tr>\\n</tbody>\\n</table>\\n<h3 id=\\\"quick-checks-or-troubleshooting\\\">Quick checks (or troubleshooting)</h3>\\n<p>From a fresh CLI environment (e.g. cmd.exe):</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li><code>echo %JAVA_HOME%</code> to confirm <code>JAVA_HOME</code> is on your <code>PATH</code> (see \\\"Java,\\\" above)</li>\\n<li><code>cmake --version</code> should work and report a version =&gt; 3.19.7</li>\\n<li><code>py</code> should work (see \\\"Python,\\\" above) -- <code>Ctrl+Z</code> exits the interactive prompt</li>\\n<li>\\n<p><code>javac</code> should work (see \\\"Java,\\\" above)Clone the repository</p>\\n</li>\\n<li>\\n<p>Create a local clone of the Carbon codebase with:\\n <code>shell\\n git clone https://msasg.visualstudio.com/DefaultCollection/Skyman/_git/Carbon</code></p>\\n<p>Here (and in the rest of the document) we assume that the source code is cloned into a subdirectory named <code>Carbon</code>. But you can select any name, by adding the target folder name at the end of the above <code>git clone</code> command.</p>\\n<p>Although the Carbon repository is using submodules for several dependencies, it is not necessary to do a recursive clone. The CMAKE process in the following step will clone the required submodules into your local repository.</p>\\n</li>\\n</ul>\",\"id\":null,\"title\":\"Checkout and Build Carbon on Windows\",\"filepath\":\"setupwinenv.md\",\"url\":\"https://openaisdktestdatastorage.blob.core.windows.net/fileupload-azure_search_index/setupwinenv.md\",\"metadata\":{\"chunking\":\"orignal document size=1407. Scores=0.24781947Org Highlight count=1.\"},\"chunk_id\":\"3\"}],\"intent\":\"[\\\"What is the most common feedback customers give about our product?\\\", \\\"What do customers say about our product?\\\", \\\"What are the common complaints or compliments about our product?\\\", \\\"What are the most frequent comments from customers about our product?\\\", \\\"What are the most common customer reviews about our product?\\\", \\\"What are the most common customer feedback about our product?\\\", \\\"What do customers think about our product?\\\", \\\"What are the most common opinions of customers about our product?\\\", \\\"What are the most common customer experiences with our product?\\\", \\\"What are the most common customer ratings for our product?\\\", \\\"What are\\\"]\"}","end_turn":false}]}},"end_turn":false,"finish_reason":null}]}

